						<summary>

						<p><hi rend="italic">Stone leaning against the front wall of the temple of Basavaṇṇa at Sahazar, a suburb of Bankapur.</hi></p>						

						<p>A.D. 1476.</p>						

						<p>This damaged inscription is dated in <hi rend="bold">Śaka 1399</hi> (expired), <hi rend="bold">Durmukhi, Kārtīka ba. 5,</hi> corresponding to <hi rend="bold">A.D. 1476, November 6, Wednesday</hi> (not verifiable).</p>						

						<p>It states that <hi rend="bold">[Bābali]-Nāyakitti,</hi> wife of <hi rend="bold">Immaḍi Siṅge-Nāyaka</hi> and daughter of <hi rend="bold">Bhimiseṭṭiya-Māyaṇṇa</hi> and <hi rend="bold">Sitamma</hi> built a well for the merit of her daughter <hi rend="bold">Dēmarasi,</hi> who died an unnatural death. The major portion of the record which is damaged extols the merit, in Sanskrit, of making a gift of water <hi rend="italic">(udaka-dāna).</hi></p>						

						</summary>
